Claimant Count and Universal Credit in Trafford

Claimant Count in Trafford

The Claimant Count indicates the number of people claiming benefits principally for the reason of being unemployed. From Jan 2020 to Feb 2021 the Claimant Count in Trafford has increased a 128.7%. The rate of claimants to residents aged 16 to 64 reached 5.4% in Feb 2021 representing an increment of 3.1% from Jan 2020.

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford

The Trafford ward with the largest share of claims in Feb 2021 was Clifford with 11.6% of all claimants within Trafford. The ward with the highest percentage change from Feb 2020 to Feb 2021 is Timperley with 240% change. However, the ward with more additional claims in this period is Clifford with 445, followed by Longford (365), Gorse Hill(355), Bucklow-St Martins(270) and Stretford(265).

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford's wards

The wards with higher claimant rate in Feb 2021 were Clifford with 10.5% and Bucklow-St Martins with 10.1%. The wards where the claimant rate has grown more from Feb 2020 to Feb 2021 are also Clifford and Bucklow-St Martins with an increase in rate of 5.2% and 4.4% respectively along with Longford with 4.4%.

In Trafford from Feb 2020 to Feb 2021 almost all age bands have at least doubled their claimant count. When considering the number of additional claims the age band 18-24 years had the highest with 1455 more claims.

Change in the Claimant Count by age bands in Trafford
Change in the Claimant Count by broad age bands in Trafford

At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 already had the highest number of claims however after the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic that started in Mar 2020 this figure increased more compared to the other age bands. The claimant rate as a proportion of the Trafords population of each age band shows a higher increase in the age bands of 25-34 and 16-24 compared to the others.

Almost half of Traffords claimants are residents of five of the 21 Traffords wards. Almost half of the claimants are under 34 years.

Claimant Count for Trafford's wards by age band

Universal Credit claims in Trafford

The Universal Credit claims in Trafford have increased 99.1% from Jan 2020 to Feb 2021. The rate of claims as a proportion of people age 16 to 64 increased form 6.1% to 12.2%. Therefore the number of Universal Credit claimants has doubled in that period.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford

The Trafford MSOA with the largest share of claims in Feb 2021 was Old Trafford with 11.1% of all Universal Credit claims in Trafford. The MSOA with the highest percentage change from Feb 2020 to Feb 2021 is Davyhulme with 178% change. However, the MSOA with more additional claims in this period is Old Trafford with 908, followed by Firswood (532), Partington(513), Gorse Hill(473) and Broadheath & Firsway(470).

Change on the Universal Credit claims for Trafford's MSOAs

The MSOAs with higher rates of Universal Credit claims in Feb 2021 were Partington with 27.1% and Old Trafford with 25.2%. The MSOAs where the rate of Universal Credit claims has grown more from Feb 2020 to Feb 2021 were also Old Trafford and Partington with 11.6% and 10.2% respectively along with Firswood with 9.3%.

In Trafford from Feb 2020 to Feb 2021 almost all 5-year age bands have increased at least an 80% in the number of Universal Credit claims. When considering the number of additional claims the 5-year age band 30-34 years had the highest with 2603 more claims.

Change in the Universal Credit claims by age nabd for Trafford

Following the start of the Covid-19 pandemic in Mar 2020 the number of claims for all ages suddenly rose from the pre-pandemic levels at a similar proportion for all age bands with the age band 16-24 rising faster in May 2020. All age bands claims are still slowly rising. At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 had the highest number of claims and also the highest rate maintaining that position after the rise from Mar 2020.

The Conditionality regimen for entitlement to Universal Credit is associated to work-related things that claimants will have to do to maintain elegibility. In Trafford the largest proportion of Universal Credit claims are in the Searching for Work category however there is also a significant proportion of claims under No work requirements.
